## Workflow : iterion_goai_to_claw_port
## Objective : Replace iterion's native agentic layer (goai) with claw-code-go.
## The team maintains both repos, so both are in scope:
##   - iterion (Go module github.com/SocialGouv/iterion) — primary repo
##   - .works/claw-code-go — pure-Go Claude Code port, currently internal/-heavy
##
## Migration approach is "bridge as a library" (decided in the planning phase):
##   - Refactor claw-code-go to expose its core via pkg/api and pkg/runtime
##   - Split the Bubble Tea TUI into a sub-module so iterion's go.sum stays slim
##   - In iterion: write model/claw_backend.go + model/claw_registry.go
##   - Drop vendor/github.com/zendev-sh/goai/ and the goai dependency
##
##   - All hot-path agents -> claude_code (backend: "claude_code") with Opus 4.7
##   - Codex used ONLY for: plan consolidation + second verdict judge
##   - Session continuity: fork for review, inherit for fix (preserves KV cache)
##
## Phases :
##   0. Analysis: Claude maps goai call sites in iterion + claw-code-go API surface
##   1. Planning: Claude plans batch -> Codex consolidates -> judge+merge
##   1b. Human gate: LLM decides if human validation is needed before impl
##   2. Implementation: Claude implements (session inherit across iterations)
##   3. Checkpoint: fork-based commit naming + iterion build/test execution
##   4. Review: Claude reviews with tools (fork from impl session)
##   5. Verdict: dual judge (Claude + Codex), both must agree, self-critique
##   6. Fix: session-inherit fix from reviewer -> back to checkpoint
##
## @group analysis: analyze, merge_analysis
## @group planning: plan_fanout, claude_plan, codex_consolidate, plan_judge_merge, plan_gate
## @group implementation: implement, simplify
## @group checkpoint: commit_namer, commit_changes, run_iterion_tests, review_scan_fanout, migration_scanner
## @group review: claude_review, verdict_fanout, claude_verdict, codex_verdict, review_verdict
## @group fix: fix

vars:
  workspace_dir: string = "${PROJECT_DIR}"

## ─── Prompts : Analysis ────────────────────────────────────────

prompt analyze_system:
  You are a senior Go architect specializing in dependency migration and SDK
  swap operations. You thoroughly examine source code, identify call sites,
  exported APIs, hook contracts, and test coverage. You produce structured,
  comprehensive migration inventories suitable for batch-by-batch execution.

prompt analyze_user:
  Analyze both codebases to produce a goai -> claw migration manifest.

  iterion repository: {{input.iterion_repo_path}}
  claw-code-go repository: {{input.claw_repo_path}}
  Migration scope notes: {{input.scope_notes}}

  For the iterion codebase, identify:
  - Every Go file importing github.com/zendev-sh/goai or github.com/zendev-sh/goai/provider
    (run: grep -rn "github.com/zendev-sh/goai" --include='*.go' .  excluding vendor/)
  - Every public/internal type defined on top of goai types
    (RequestInfo, ResponseInfo, StepResult, ToolCallInfo adapters in model/hooks.go)
  - The three generation strategies in model/goai_backend.go (structured / text / text+tools+schema)
  - The retry loop and isRetryable predicate (currently in model/goai_backend.go)
  - The provider/model-id parser in model/registry.go
  - The tool adapter in tool/adapter.go
  - Every example .iter and test fixture referencing backend: "goai"
    (grep examples/*.iter e2e/**/*.iter for the literal string "goai")

  For the claw-code-go codebase, identify:
  - Internal packages that need promotion to public:
    * internal/api -> pkg/api (types.go, client.go, provider.go, sse.go, providers/*)
    * internal/runtime core (conversation.go, config.go, events.go, compact.go,
      provider_factory.go, loop_*.go, errors.go, permissions.go) -> pkg/runtime
    * internal/permissions (Manager, PermissionMode) -> pkg/permissions
    * internal/hooks (HookRunner) -> pkg/hooks
  - Internal packages that should STAY internal (do NOT promote):
    * internal/mcp (iterion has its own MCP manager)
    * internal/tools concrete implementations (iterion supplies tools via delegate.ToolDef)
    * internal/tui, internal/commands, internal/lsp, internal/auth (TUI-specific)
    * internal/runtime/{lane,policy,recovery,remote} (advanced runtime extensions)
  - The TUI dependencies in go.mod that need to move to a sub-module:
    * charmbracelet/{bubbles,bubbletea,colorprofile,lipgloss,x/*}
    * atotto/clipboard, mattn/go-isatty, etc.

  Produce a structured manifest with per-target-file status:
  PORTED, PARTIAL, MISSING, BLOCKED.
  BLOCKED = downstream work depends on something not yet promoted.

prompt merge_analysis_system:
  You are a senior architect specializing in synthesis.
  You receive a raw migration analysis and produce a clean, structured
  manifest. Ensure every iterion call site and every claw promotion target
  is accounted for.

prompt merge_analysis_user:
  Produce a structured migration manifest from this analysis.

  Analysis:
  {{input.analysis}}

  iterion repo: {{input.iterion_repo_path}}
  claw-code-go repo: {{input.claw_repo_path}}

  Produce a manifest that:
  - Lists every iterion file with a goai import (status: PORTED, PARTIAL, MISSING)
  - Lists every claw-code-go internal package that must be promoted
    (status: PORTED, PARTIAL, MISSING, BLOCKED)
  - Identifies new files to create in iterion (claw_backend.go, claw_registry.go,
    claw_hooks.go, claw_tools.go)
  - Establishes dependency ordering (claw promotion BEFORE iterion bridge BEFORE goai delete)
  - Estimates complexity per batch (low, medium, high)
  - Computes overall migration percentage
    (resolved_call_sites + ported_promotions) / (total_call_sites + total_promotions)

## ─── Prompts : Migration Planning ──────────────────────────────

prompt port_plan_system:
  You are a senior engineer specializing in Go SDK migration.
  You produce detailed, ordered, dependency-aware migration plans.
  You understand the goai -> claw mapping:
  - goai.GenerateText() tool loop -> claw runtime ConversationLoop or pkg/api send
  - goai.GenerateObject[T]() with WithExplicitSchema -> synthetic structured_output tool
  - goai.WithProviderOptions(reasoning_effort) -> per-provider mapping
  - goai hooks (RequestInfo/ResponseInfo/StepResult/ToolCallInfo) -> claw StreamEvent
  - goai.WithMaxRetries(0) -> disable claw HTTP retry, iterion owns retry
  - goai provider factories (anthropic.Chat, openai.Chat) -> claw provider factories
  - Two-pass execution (tools + schema coercion) -> hand-roll inside claw_backend

  Locked decisions for this migration:
  - Bridge approach: claw-code-go is a separate Go module dependency, NOT vendored
  - TUI split: claw-code-go/tui/ becomes a separate sub-module with its own go.mod
  - Provider scope validated end-to-end: anthropic + openai only
    (bedrock, vertex, foundry, xai, dashscope: code present, untested)
  - BackendGoai constant: HARD RENAME to BackendClaw, no deprecated alias
    (sweep examples/*.iter and e2e/**/*.iter for backend: "goai" -> "claw")
  - Two-pass schema: hand-roll synthetic structured_output tool inside
    iterion's model/claw_backend.go (do NOT depend on claw's tools.StructuredOutputTool)

prompt port_plan_user:
  Produce a migration plan for the next batch.

  Migration manifest:
  {{input.feature_manifest}}

  Previous porting progress:
  {{input.previous_progress}}

  Previous review feedback:
  {{input.previous_feedback}}

  Batch history (all previous verdict outcomes for cross-batch learning):
  {{input.batch_history}}

  Instructions:
  1. Review the batch history to understand what was already attempted and what worked
  2. Select the next logical batch (respect dependency ordering):
     - Phase A: claw-code-go internal -> pkg promotions (api first, runtime second)
     - Phase B: TUI split into sub-module
     - Phase C: iterion bridge files (model/claw_registry.go, model/claw_backend.go,
       model/claw_hooks.go, model/claw_tools.go)
     - Phase D: rewire executor.go, cli/run.go, delegate/delegate.go, tool/adapter.go,
       model/events.go, model/hooks.go
     - Phase E: delete vendor/github.com/zendev-sh/goai, drop go.mod require line
     - Phase F: rename backend: "goai" -> "claw" in all .iter files and test fixtures
     - Phase G: update unit + e2e tests
  3. For each file, describe the source change and the target shape
  4. Specify files to create or modify in BOTH iterion and claw-code-go
  5. Include a test plan: which iterion packages must be re-tested after this batch
  6. Do NOT touch internal/mcp, internal/tools concrete impls, or TUI sub-module from iterion
  7. Avoid re-attempting batches that stagnated previously without a new approach

## ─── Prompts : Plan Consolidation ──────────────────────────────

prompt consolidate_plan_system:
  You are an independent plan reviewer and consolidator for an iterion
  goai-to-claw migration project. You receive a migration plan produced
  by another engineer and must:
  1. VALIDATE: check dependency ordering (claw promotion before bridge,
     bridge before goai delete), test coverage, and completeness
  2. CONSOLIDATE: strengthen the plan by adding missing details, fixing
     ordering issues, ensuring every goai call site is addressed
  3. CHALLENGE: identify risks, blind spots, and potential pitfalls
     (especially: bootstrap safety, retry semantics, two-pass schema,
     hook event fidelity, session continuity through claude_code/codex backends
     which DO NOT use goai or claw — they shell out)

  Be pragmatic: minor style preferences should not block. Focus on
  correctness, completeness, and dependency ordering.

prompt consolidate_plan_user:
  Review and consolidate this migration plan.

  Original plan:
  {{input.original_plan}}

  Migration manifest:
  {{input.feature_manifest}}

  Produce a consolidated plan that:
  - Preserves the good elements of the original
  - Fixes any dependency ordering issues
  - Adds missing migration strategies (e.g., synthetic structured_output tool)
  - Strengthens the test plan (unit per package, e2e stub suite, build success)
  - Lists any remaining concerns in issues[]

## ─── Prompts : Plan Judge + Merge ─────────────────────────────

prompt plan_judge_merge_system:
  You are a senior architect who evaluates a migration plan and its
  independent consolidation review.

  You must:
  1. If the consolidated plan is sound (ready=true): produce a final
     merged_plan integrating the best of both the original and consolidated
  2. If not (ready=false): list the blocking issues in issues[] to guide
     a new planning iteration

  Be pragmatic: minor suggestions should NOT block. Only major issues
  (wrong dependencies, missing critical files, broken bootstrap) justify
  rejection.

prompt plan_judge_merge_user:
  Evaluate this migration plan and its consolidation.

  Original plan (Claude):
  {{input.claude_plan}}

  Consolidated plan (Codex):
  {{input.codex_plan}}

  Migration manifest:
  {{input.feature_manifest}}

  If the plans are of sufficient quality (ready=true),
  produce a final merged plan in merged_plan.
  Otherwise, list the blocking issues in issues[].

## ─── Prompts : Human Gate ──────────────────────────────────────

prompt plan_gate_system:
  You are a plan validation gate for an iterion goai-to-claw migration.
  You receive a validated plan and must decide if human review is needed
  before starting implementation.

  Set needs_human_input=true when:
  - The batch deletes vendor/github.com/zendev-sh/goai or removes the go.mod require
    (irreversible, late-stage)
  - The batch renames the BackendGoai constant or sweeps backend: "goai" in .iter
    (touches >5 example files at once)
  - The batch performs the TUI sub-module split (changes claw-code-go/go.mod root)
  - The plan involves breaking changes to delegate.Backend or NodeExecutor interfaces
  - The estimated scope is very large (>10 files to create/modify)

  Set needs_human_input=false when:
  - The batch promotes a single internal package to pkg/ (incremental, reversible)
  - The batch creates a new bridge file in iterion (additive, no goai removal yet)
  - The plan is clear and unambiguous

  Always fill in the plan_summary and risk_assessment fields regardless.

## ─── Prompts : Implementation ──────────────────────────────────

prompt port_impl_system:
  You are an expert Go developer specializing in dependency migration.
  You apply migration plans precisely. Key rules:
  - When promoting an internal package: keep API surface stable, only change
    import paths (grep all callers in claw-code-go and update)
  - When wiring iterion bridge files: the new code must satisfy delegate.Backend
    and emit the same EventHooks events as model/goai_backend.go
  - When deleting goai: do it in ONE batch — vendor dir, go.mod require,
    and final import sweep together (otherwise build breaks halfway)
  - Always run `devbox run -- go build ./...` and `devbox run -- go vet ./...`
    after changes to verify the tree compiles

  Bootstrap safety rule: the `./iterion` binary running this workflow is
  statically linked at workflow start. You can edit any source file freely;
  the running host process is unaffected. Tests run go build/vet/test against
  the source tree, not the host binary.

  Locked decisions to honor:
  - Bridge, not embed (claw-code-go imported as Go module dependency)
  - TUI -> separate sub-module under claw-code-go/tui/
  - Hard rename BackendGoai -> BackendClaw (no alias)
  - anthropic + openai providers validated end-to-end; others ship dark
  - Two-pass schema: hand-roll the structured_output tool inside iterion

prompt port_impl_user:
  Apply the next batch of changes according to this validated plan.

  Migration plan:
  {{input.validated_plan}}

  Migration manifest:
  {{input.feature_manifest}}

  iterion repo: {{input.iterion_repo_path}}
  claw-code-go repo: {{input.claw_repo_path}}

  Previous feedback (failing tests or unresolved issues):
  {{input.previous_feedback}}

  Instructions:
  1. Read the relevant source files to understand exact behavior before editing
  2. Apply edits to BOTH repos as needed (claw promotion + iterion wiring)
  3. Update or write tests for each modified package
  4. Ensure existing iterion tests still pass for unmodified packages
  5. Run go vet and go build after each modification
  6. If a batch deletes goai: the build MUST be green at the end
     (no half-applied state)

## ─── Prompts : Simplify ───────────────────────────────────────

prompt simplify_system:
  You are a senior Go engineer focused on code quality and simplification.
  You review recently changed code for reuse opportunities, quality issues,
  and efficiency improvements, then fix any issues found.

  Focus on:
  - Dead code removal (orphaned goai-shaped helpers after the rewire)
  - Deduplication (extract shared helpers from copy-pasted blocks)
  - Idiomatic Go patterns (error wrapping, interface compliance, naming)
  - Unnecessary complexity (over-abstraction, premature generalization)
  - Missing error handling on critical paths

  Do NOT:
  - Refactor working code that isn't part of the recent changes
  - Add features or change behavior
  - Add comments or documentation unless code is genuinely unclear
  - Touch test files unless they have compilation errors
  - Re-introduce backward-compat shims for the removed goai backend

  Run go vet and go build on iterion when done.

prompt simplify_user:
  Review and simplify the code changes from this implementation session.
  Focus on the files that were just created or modified.
  Fix quality issues, remove dead code, deduplicate, and ensure idiomatic Go.

## ─── Prompts : Migration Scanner ──────────────────────────────

prompt parity_scan_system:
  You are a deterministic migration scanner for the iterion goai-to-claw port.
  Your ONLY job is to produce an accurate, up-to-date migration manifest.

  You work with a FIXED CHECKLIST approach:
  - The previous manifest contains the authoritative list of goai call sites
    and claw-code-go promotion targets
  - You MUST preserve every entry — never drop entries
  - You MUST preserve the status of entries you don't inspect

  INCREMENTAL UPDATE RULES:
  - Only re-evaluate entries currently MISSING, PARTIAL, or BLOCKED
  - For PORTED entries: keep them as PORTED unless the impl artifact
    mentions changes to that entry
  - For MISSING/PARTIAL/BLOCKED entries: use your tools to verify the
    actual state. Only change status if you verify with code.

  STATUSES:
  - PORTED: change applied (call site removed, package promoted, file deleted)
  - PARTIAL: partially applied (e.g., type promoted but tests missing)
  - MISSING: not yet started
  - BLOCKED: depends on another entry not yet PORTED
  - SKIPPED: intentionally not migrated. ONLY a human can mark SKIPPED.

  DETERMINISTIC METRICS to compute (use search_codebase / grep / tree):
  - total_goai_call_sites: count of files importing zendev-sh/goai outside vendor/
    (cmd: grep -rln "github.com/zendev-sh/goai" --include='*.go' . | grep -v vendor)
  - vendor_goai_present: ls vendor/github.com/zendev-sh/goai exits 0
  - goai_in_gomod: grep zendev-sh/goai go.mod returns a require line
  - blocking_internal_packages: list claw-code-go/internal/{api,runtime,permissions,hooks}
    paths still referenced from any external caller path
  - tests_passing: derived from the test_results input field
  - migration_percentage: (resolved + ported) / (total + total_promotions) * 100
    Computed from PORTED status counts; never decreases except on regression evidence.

prompt parity_scan_user:
  Update the migration manifest incrementally.

  iterion repo: {{input.iterion_repo_path}}
  claw-code-go repo: {{input.claw_repo_path}}

  Previous manifest (AUTHORITATIVE CHECKLIST):
  {{input.feature_manifest}}

  Instructions:
  1. Start from the previous manifest — it is the checklist
  2. For each MISSING/PARTIAL/BLOCKED entry, run the deterministic check
  3. Only upgrade status (MISSING->PARTIAL, PARTIAL->PORTED) if verified by code
  4. NEVER downgrade a PORTED entry without concrete regression evidence
  5. Preserve all entries — total counts must stay the same
  6. Recompute parity_percentage from PORTED counts
  7. Set vendor_goai_present and goai_in_gomod from filesystem checks

## ─── Prompts : Commit ─────────────────────────────────────────

prompt commit_namer_system:
  You are in a session where code work was just completed.
  Generate a semantic commit message based on what was done SINCE THE
  LAST COMMIT in this session. Focus on the most recent work only, not
  the full session history.
  Format: type(scope): description
  Types: feat, fix, refactor, test, docs, chore
  Scope: the iterion package most affected, OR "claw" if the change is
  inside .works/claw-code-go (use "claw-api", "claw-runtime", etc. for
  more specificity)
  Description: concise, specific to THIS iteration's changes

prompt commit_namer_user:
  Generate a commit message for the changes made since the last commit.
  Focus on what was done most recently in this session, not the full history.

## ─── Prompts : Review ──────────────────────────────────────────

prompt parity_review_system:
  You are a meticulous code reviewer specializing in Go SDK migrations.
  You combine THREE roles:
  1. REVIEWER: verify the migration batch was applied correctly
     (the iterion call sites changed, the claw promotions are visible,
     the bridge code matches the goai semantics being replaced)
  2. JUDGE: produce a verdict (approved=true/false)
  3. FIX PLANNER: if the verdict is negative, produce a concrete, actionable
     fix plan describing exactly what needs to be corrected

  You have access to file reading tools. USE THEM to read both codebases.
  Do NOT rely solely on the implementation summary — verify the actual code.

  Classify each issue as BLOCKER or SUGGESTION:
  - BLOCKER: build fails, tests fail, goai still imported where it shouldn't be,
    a promoted package still referenced via internal/ path, hook events missing,
    retry logic broken, structured-output coercion broken, security issue.
    Things that would break a real user.
  - SUGGESTION: style differences, non-idiomatic patterns, missing comments,
    minor format differences, suboptimal but working code.

  Set approved=true if there are ZERO blockers (suggestions are OK).
  Set approved=false only if there are blockers.

prompt parity_review_user:
  Review this migration batch.

  Implementation result:
  {{input.implementation}}

  Migration manifest (may be stale — verify against actual code):
  {{input.feature_manifest}}

  iterion repo: {{input.iterion_repo_path}}
  claw-code-go repo: {{input.claw_repo_path}}

  Test results:
  {{input.test_results}}

  INSTRUCTIONS:
  1. USE YOUR TOOLS to read the actual files claimed to be changed
  2. For each entry in the CURRENT BATCH, verify:
     - The change was actually applied (read the file, find the diff)
     - The build still passes (check test_results)
     - The tests for affected packages still pass
     - No half-applied state (e.g., goai still imported AND claw bridge wired
       at the same time — that breaks the build)
  3. Mark each entry PASS or FAIL with justification citing code
  4. Classify issues as BLOCKER or SUGGESTION
  5. Set approved=true if zero blockers
  6. If approved=false, produce fix_plan for BLOCKERS ONLY
  7. Use the parity_scan data (deterministic counts) for context on overall
     project progress. Focus your review on the CURRENT BATCH only.

## ─── Prompts : Verdict (dual judge, two-phase) ─────────────────

prompt parity_verdict_system:
  You are a final judge for an iterion goai-to-claw migration iteration.
  You evaluate using blocker/suggestion classification and stagnation detection.

  CLASSIFICATION:
  Separate the review's issues into:
  - blockers[]: build/test breakage, goai imports remaining where they
    shouldn't, broken hook semantics, broken retry, broken structured output
  - suggestions[]: style, naming, non-idiomatic Go, polish

  BATCH COMPLETION:
  Set batch_complete based on the acceptance_threshold:
  - "strict": batch_complete=true only if ZERO blockers AND zero suggestions
  - "normal" (default): batch_complete=true if ZERO blockers (suggestions OK)
  - "lenient": batch_complete=true if blockers are minor and non-security

  STAGNATION DETECTION:
  Compare with previous_verdict (if provided). If the same blockers appear
  in both the current and previous verdict, the fix loop is stagnating.
  If stagnating, set batch_complete=true anyway — the remaining issues
  will be carried to the next planning cycle as feedback.

  OVERALL MIGRATION COMPLETE:
  Use the parity_scan data (deterministic call-site/file counts) to assess
  overall progress. Set overall_parity=true ONLY when ALL of the following hold:
  - total_goai_call_sites == 0 (or all remaining are inside vendor/, expected to be deleted)
  - vendor_goai_present == false
  - goai_in_gomod == false
  - tests_passing == true
  - blocking_internal_packages is empty
  - migration_percentage >= 100

  SELF-CRITIQUE (two-phase):
  Phase 1: Rigorously evaluate each current-batch entry.
  Phase 2: For each provisional blocker, ask THREE questions:
    a) "Would this break a real user in production?"
    b) "Is this about the current batch or a future batch?"
    c) "Has this exact issue appeared in the previous verdict already?"
  Reclassify false positives as suggestions. Reclassify stagnant blockers
  as suggestions (they'll be addressed in the next planning cycle).

prompt parity_verdict_user:
  Evaluate this migration iteration.

  Implementation:
  {{input.implementation}}

  Review:
  {{input.review}}

  Test results:
  {{input.test_results}}

  Migration manifest:
  {{input.feature_manifest}}

  Parity scan (deterministic counts):
  {{input.parity_scan}}

  Previous verdict (for stagnation detection):
  {{input.previous_verdict}}

  Acceptance threshold:
  {{input.acceptance_threshold}}

  Instructions:
  1. Classify review issues as blockers[] or suggestions[]
  2. Self-critique each blocker (would it break production? is it stagnant?)
  3. Detect stagnation: same blockers as previous verdict = stagnating
  4. Set batch_complete per acceptance_threshold (default: zero blockers)
     If stagnating, set batch_complete=true regardless
  5. Use parity_scan data for parity_percentage
  6. Set overall_parity=true ONLY if migration is fully complete (see system)
  7. Only list real, non-stagnant blockers in blockers[]
  8. Set batch_tokens to the sum of _tokens fields from implementation,
     review, and verdict inputs (for cost tracking per batch)

## ─── Prompts : Verdict Synthesis ────────────────────────────────

prompt verdict_synthesis_system:
  You are the final arbiter of an iterion goai-to-claw migration iteration.
  You receive two independent verdict evaluations (from Claude and Codex).

  Rules for batch_complete:
  - If BOTH judges set batch_complete=true -> batch_complete=true
  - If only ONE judge has blockers, evaluate carefully: are they real
    production-breaking issues or cosmetic? A single judge's suggestion
    should not block the batch.
  - If both judges detected stagnation -> batch_complete=true (move on)

  Rules for overall_parity:
  - BOTH judges must agree on overall_parity=true
  - Use the LOWER parity_percentage of the two

  Rules for blocker/suggestion merge:
  - Issue flagged as blocker by BOTH judges -> blocker (very likely real)
  - Issue flagged as blocker by ONE judge -> evaluate carefully, likely suggestion
  - Deduplicate across judges

  Acceptance threshold: {{input.acceptance_threshold}}
  Apply the threshold when deciding batch_complete (strict/normal/lenient).

prompt verdict_synthesis_user:
  Synthesize these two independent verdicts.

  Claude verdict:
  {{input.claude_verdict}}

  Codex verdict:
  {{input.codex_verdict}}

  Migration manifest:
  {{input.feature_manifest}}

  Acceptance threshold: {{input.acceptance_threshold}}

  Produce a final synthesized verdict with:
  - batch_complete: true if batch passes per threshold (normal = zero blockers)
  - overall_parity: true only if migration is fully complete
    (zero goai imports, no vendor dir, no go.mod require, all tests pass)
  - blockers[]: real production-breaking issues agreed by both judges
  - suggestions[]: cosmetic/style issues for future improvement

## ─── Prompts : Fix ─────────────────────────────────────────────

prompt fix_system:
  You are in a code review session. You previously performed a review
  and identified problems with a goai-to-claw migration batch.
  Now you must EXECUTE the fix plan that was produced.

  Apply the corrections described in the fix plan.
  Be methodical: treat each issue one by one.
  Verify your work by re-reading the files after modifications.
  Run go vet and go build on iterion when done.

prompt fix_user:
  Execute the following fix plan on the iterion + claw-code-go repos.

  Fix plan:
  {{input.fix_plan}}

  Migration manifest:
  {{input.feature_manifest}}

  iterion repo: {{input.iterion_repo_path}}
  claw-code-go repo: {{input.claw_repo_path}}

  Apply the corrections and verify that the migration progresses.

## ─── Schemas ───────────────────────────────────────────────────

schema workflow_input:
  iterion_repo_path: string
  claw_repo_path: string
  scope_notes: string

schema analyze_input:
  iterion_repo_path: string
  claw_repo_path: string
  scope_notes: string

schema analysis_output:
  iterion_goai_call_sites: string[]
  iterion_files_to_create: string[]
  claw_packages_to_promote: string[]
  claw_packages_to_keep_internal: string[]
  tui_deps_to_split: string[]
  bridge_files_to_create: string[]
  dependency_order: string[]
  complexity_estimates: string[]

schema merge_analysis_input:
  analysis: json
  iterion_repo_path: string
  claw_repo_path: string

schema feature_manifest:
  total_goai_call_sites: int
  resolved_call_sites: string[]
  remaining_call_sites: string[]
  blocking_internal_packages: string[]
  ported_promotions: string[]
  failed_promotions: string[]
  tests_passing: bool
  vendor_goai_present: bool
  goai_in_gomod: bool
  parity_percentage: string
  dependency_order: string[]

schema port_plan_input:
  feature_manifest: json
  previous_progress: string
  previous_feedback: string
  batch_history: json

schema port_plan_output:
  summary: string
  batch_features: string[]
  ordered_steps: string[]
  migration_strategies: string[]
  files_to_create: string[]
  files_to_modify: string[]
  test_plan: string[]
  risks: string[]

schema consolidate_plan_input:
  original_plan: json
  feature_manifest: json

schema consolidate_plan_output:
  summary: string
  batch_features: string[]
  ordered_steps: string[]
  migration_strategies: string[]
  files_to_create: string[]
  files_to_modify: string[]
  test_plan: string[]
  risks: string[]
  issues: string[]

schema plan_judge_merge_input:
  claude_plan: json
  codex_plan: json
  feature_manifest: json

schema plan_judge_merge_output:
  ready: bool
  merged_plan: json
  issues: string[]

schema plan_gate_input:
  validated_plan: json
  feature_manifest: json

schema plan_gate_output:
  plan_summary: string
  risk_assessment: string
  questions: string[]
  proceed: bool

schema impl_input:
  validated_plan: json
  feature_manifest: json
  iterion_repo_path: string
  claw_repo_path: string
  previous_feedback: string

schema impl_output:
  applied: bool
  summary: string
  files_changed: string[]
  features_ported: string[]
  tests_added: string[]

schema test_result:
  passed: bool
  exit_code: int
  logs: string
  failed_tests: string[]

schema parity_scan_input:
  iterion_repo_path: string
  claw_repo_path: string
  feature_manifest: json

schema review_input:
  implementation: json
  feature_manifest: json
  iterion_repo_path: string
  claw_repo_path: string
  test_results: json
  parity_scan: json

schema review_output:
  summary: string
  blockers: string[]
  suggestions: string[]
  feature_verdicts: string[]
  approved: bool
  fix_plan: string

schema verdict_input:
  implementation: json
  review: json
  test_results: json
  feature_manifest: json
  parity_scan: json
  previous_verdict: json
  acceptance_threshold: string

schema verdict_output:
  batch_complete: bool
  overall_parity: bool
  blockers: string[]
  suggestions: string[]
  parity_percentage: string
  confidence: string [enum: "low", "medium", "high"]
  batch_tokens: int

schema verdict_synthesis_input:
  claude_verdict: json
  codex_verdict: json
  feature_manifest: json
  acceptance_threshold: string

schema parity_verdict:
  batch_complete: bool
  overall_parity: bool
  blockers: string[]
  suggestions: string[]
  parity_percentage: string
  confidence: string [enum: "low", "medium", "high"]
  batch_tokens: int

schema commit_name_output:
  type: string [enum: "feat", "fix", "refactor", "test", "docs", "chore"]
  scope: string
  description: string
  full_message: string

schema commit_tool_input:
  full_message: string
  iterion_repo_path: string
  claw_repo_path: string

schema commit_result:
  success: bool
  output: string

schema fix_input:
  fix_plan: string
  feature_manifest: json
  iterion_repo_path: string
  claw_repo_path: string

schema fix_output:
  applied: bool
  summary: string
  files_changed: string[]
  features_fixed: string[]

## ─── Nodes : Phase 0 — Analysis ───────────────────────────────

agent analyze:
  backend: "claude_code"
  input: analyze_input
  output: analysis_output
  publish: raw_analysis
  system: analyze_system
  user: analyze_user
  session: fresh
  reasoning_effort: high

agent merge_analysis:
  backend: "claude_code"
  input: merge_analysis_input
  output: feature_manifest
  publish: feature_manifest
  system: merge_analysis_system
  user: merge_analysis_user
  session: fresh

## ─── Nodes : Phase 1 — Planning + Consolidation ───────────────

router plan_fanout:
  mode: fan_out_all

agent claude_plan:
  backend: "claude_code"
  input: port_plan_input
  output: port_plan_output
  publish: claude_plan_output
  system: port_plan_system
  user: port_plan_user
  session: fresh

agent codex_consolidate:
  backend: "codex"
  input: consolidate_plan_input
  output: consolidate_plan_output
  publish: codex_plan_output
  system: consolidate_plan_system
  user: consolidate_plan_user
  session: fresh

agent plan_judge_merge:
  await: wait_all
  backend: "claude_code"
  input: plan_judge_merge_input
  output: plan_judge_merge_output
  publish: merged_plan
  system: plan_judge_merge_system
  user: plan_judge_merge_user
  session: fresh

## ─── Node : Phase 1b — Human Gate (LLM decides) ───────────────

human plan_gate:
  input: plan_gate_input
  output: plan_gate_output
  interaction: llm_or_human
  model: "openai/gpt-5.4-mini"
  system: plan_gate_system

## ─── Nodes : Phase 2 — Implementation ─────────────────────────

agent implement:
  backend: "claude_code"
  input: impl_input
  output: impl_output
  publish: implementation
  system: port_impl_system
  user: port_impl_user
  session: inherit

## ─── Nodes : Phase 2b — Simplify ───────────────────────────────

agent simplify:
  backend: "claude_code"
  output: impl_output
  publish: implementation
  system: simplify_system
  user: simplify_user
  session: inherit

## ─── Nodes : Phase 3 — Checkpoint (commit + test) ─────────────

agent commit_namer:
  backend: "claude_code"
  output: commit_name_output
  system: commit_namer_system
  user: commit_namer_user
  session: fork
  readonly: true

## Commits both repos: iterion always; claw-code-go only if it changed.
## `git diff --cached --quiet` exits non-zero when there are staged changes;
## the `||` runs the commit only in that case.
tool commit_changes:
  command: "git -C {{input.iterion_repo_path}} add -A && (git -C {{input.iterion_repo_path}} diff --cached --quiet || git -C {{input.iterion_repo_path}} commit -m {{input.full_message}}) && git -C {{input.claw_repo_path}} add -A && (git -C {{input.claw_repo_path}} diff --cached --quiet || git -C {{input.claw_repo_path}} commit -m {{input.full_message}})"
  input: commit_tool_input
  output: commit_result

## Build + vet iterion against the source tree. The host binary running this
## workflow is unaffected by source edits (statically linked).
tool run_iterion_tests:
  command: "export PATH=/workspaces/iterion/.devbox/nix/profile/default/bin:$PATH && cd {{input.iterion_repo_path}} && go build ./... && go vet ./..."
  output: test_result

## ─── Nodes : Phase 3b — Parallel Review + Migration Scan ──────

router review_scan_fanout:
  mode: fan_out_all

agent migration_scanner:
  backend: "claude_code"
  input: parity_scan_input
  output: feature_manifest
  publish: feature_manifest
  system: parity_scan_system
  user: parity_scan_user
  session: fresh
  tools: [read_file, list_files, search_codebase, tree]
  tool_max_steps: 20
  readonly: true

## ─── Nodes : Phase 4 — Review (fork from impl) ────────────────

agent claude_review:
  backend: "claude_code"
  input: review_input
  output: review_output
  publish: claude_review_report
  system: parity_review_system
  user: parity_review_user
  session: fork
  tools: [read_file, list_files, search_codebase, tree, git_diff]
  tool_max_steps: 15
  readonly: true

## ─── Nodes : Phase 5 — Dual Verdict (Claude + Codex) ──────────

router verdict_fanout:
  mode: fan_out_all

judge claude_verdict:
  backend: "claude_code"
  input: verdict_input
  output: verdict_output
  publish: claude_verdict_report
  system: parity_verdict_system
  user: parity_verdict_user
  session: fresh

judge codex_verdict:
  backend: "codex"
  input: verdict_input
  output: verdict_output
  publish: codex_verdict_report
  system: parity_verdict_system
  user: parity_verdict_user
  session: fresh

judge review_verdict:
  await: wait_all
  backend: "claude_code"
  input: verdict_synthesis_input
  output: parity_verdict
  publish: parity_verdict_report
  system: verdict_synthesis_system
  user: verdict_synthesis_user
  session: fresh

## ─── Nodes : Phase 6 — Fix (session inherit from reviewer) ────

agent fix:
  backend: "claude_code"
  input: fix_input
  output: fix_output
  publish: implementation
  system: fix_system
  user: fix_user
  session: inherit

## ─── Workflow ──────────────────────────────────────────────────

workflow iterion_goai_to_claw_port:
  vars:
    iterion_repo_path: string
    claw_repo_path: string
    scope_notes: string = ""
    acceptance_threshold: string = "normal"

  entry: analyze

  budget:
    max_parallel_branches: 3
    max_duration: "12h"
    max_cost_usd: 300
    max_tokens: 50000000
    max_iterations: 200

  ## ═══ Phase 0 : Analysis ════════════════════════════════════════

  analyze -> merge_analysis with {
    analysis: "{{outputs.analyze}}",
    iterion_repo_path: "{{vars.iterion_repo_path}}",
    claw_repo_path: "{{vars.claw_repo_path}}"
  }

  ## ═══ Phase 1 : Planning + Consolidation ════════════════════════

  merge_analysis -> plan_fanout with {
    feature_manifest: "{{outputs.merge_analysis}}",
    previous_progress: "",
    previous_feedback: ""
  }

  plan_fanout -> claude_plan with {
    feature_manifest: "{{input.feature_manifest}}",
    previous_progress: "{{input.previous_progress}}",
    previous_feedback: "{{input.previous_feedback}}"
  }

  plan_fanout -> codex_consolidate with {
    original_plan: "{{input.feature_manifest}}",
    feature_manifest: "{{input.feature_manifest}}"
  }

  claude_plan -> plan_judge_merge with {
    claude_plan: "{{outputs.claude_plan}}",
    feature_manifest: "{{artifacts.feature_manifest}}"
  }

  codex_consolidate -> plan_judge_merge with {
    codex_plan: "{{outputs.codex_consolidate}}"
  }

  ## Plan OK -> human gate
  plan_judge_merge -> plan_gate when ready with {
    validated_plan: "{{outputs.plan_judge_merge.merged_plan}}",
    feature_manifest: "{{artifacts.feature_manifest}}"
  }

  ## Plan KO -> back to planning with feedback
  plan_judge_merge -> plan_fanout when not ready as plan_loop(4) with {
    feature_manifest: "{{artifacts.feature_manifest}}",
    previous_progress: "",
    previous_feedback: "{{outputs.plan_judge_merge.issues}}"
  }

  ## ═══ Phase 1b : Human Gate ═════════════════════════════════════

  plan_gate -> implement when proceed with {
    validated_plan: "{{artifacts.merged_plan}}",
    feature_manifest: "{{artifacts.feature_manifest}}",
    iterion_repo_path: "{{vars.iterion_repo_path}}",
    claw_repo_path: "{{vars.claw_repo_path}}",
    previous_feedback: "{{artifacts.parity_verdict_report}}"
  }

  plan_gate -> plan_fanout when not proceed as plan_loop(4) with {
    feature_manifest: "{{artifacts.feature_manifest}}",
    previous_progress: "",
    previous_feedback: "{{outputs.plan_gate.questions}}"
  }

  ## ═══ Phase 2 : Implementation ═════════════════════════════════

  implement -> simplify with {
    _session_id: "{{outputs.implement._session_id}}"
  }

  ## ═══ Phase 2b : Simplify ══════════════════════════════════════

  simplify -> commit_namer with {
    _session_id: "{{outputs.simplify._session_id}}"
  }

  ## ═══ Phase 3 : Checkpoint (commit + test) ═════════════════════

  commit_namer -> commit_changes with {
    full_message: "{{outputs.commit_namer.full_message}}",
    iterion_repo_path: "{{vars.iterion_repo_path}}",
    claw_repo_path: "{{vars.claw_repo_path}}"
  }

  commit_changes -> run_iterion_tests with {
    iterion_repo_path: "{{vars.iterion_repo_path}}"
  }

  ## ═══ Phase 3b : Parallel Review + Migration Scan ══════════════
  ## Both run in parallel after tests. Migration scanner publishes the
  ## updated feature_manifest artifact. Review and verdict read it from
  ## artifacts.

  run_iterion_tests -> review_scan_fanout with {
    _session_id: "{{outputs.simplify._session_id}}",
    implementation: "{{artifacts.implementation}}",
    feature_manifest: "{{artifacts.feature_manifest}}",
    iterion_repo_path: "{{vars.iterion_repo_path}}",
    claw_repo_path: "{{vars.claw_repo_path}}",
    test_results: "{{outputs.run_iterion_tests}}"
  }

  review_scan_fanout -> migration_scanner with {
    iterion_repo_path: "{{input.iterion_repo_path}}",
    claw_repo_path: "{{input.claw_repo_path}}",
    feature_manifest: "{{input.feature_manifest}}"
  }

  review_scan_fanout -> claude_review with {
    _session_id: "{{input._session_id}}",
    implementation: "{{input.implementation}}",
    feature_manifest: "{{input.feature_manifest}}",
    iterion_repo_path: "{{input.iterion_repo_path}}",
    claw_repo_path: "{{input.claw_repo_path}}",
    test_results: "{{input.test_results}}"
  }

  ## ═══ Phase 5 : Dual Verdict (Claude + Codex judge) ════════════

  claude_review -> verdict_fanout with {
    implementation: "{{artifacts.implementation}}",
    review: "{{outputs.claude_review}}",
    test_results: "{{outputs.run_iterion_tests}}",
    feature_manifest: "{{artifacts.feature_manifest}}",
    parity_scan: "{{artifacts.feature_manifest}}",
    previous_verdict: "{{artifacts.parity_verdict_report}}",
    acceptance_threshold: "{{vars.acceptance_threshold}}"
  }

  migration_scanner -> verdict_fanout with {}

  verdict_fanout -> claude_verdict with {
    implementation: "{{input.implementation}}",
    review: "{{input.review}}",
    test_results: "{{input.test_results}}",
    feature_manifest: "{{input.feature_manifest}}",
    parity_scan: "{{input.parity_scan}}",
    previous_verdict: "{{input.previous_verdict}}",
    acceptance_threshold: "{{input.acceptance_threshold}}"
  }

  verdict_fanout -> codex_verdict with {
    implementation: "{{input.implementation}}",
    review: "{{input.review}}",
    test_results: "{{input.test_results}}",
    feature_manifest: "{{input.feature_manifest}}",
    parity_scan: "{{input.parity_scan}}",
    previous_verdict: "{{input.previous_verdict}}",
    acceptance_threshold: "{{input.acceptance_threshold}}"
  }

  claude_verdict -> review_verdict with {
    claude_verdict: "{{outputs.claude_verdict}}",
    feature_manifest: "{{artifacts.feature_manifest}}",
    acceptance_threshold: "{{vars.acceptance_threshold}}"
  }

  codex_verdict -> review_verdict with {
    codex_verdict: "{{outputs.codex_verdict}}"
  }

  ## ═══ Phase 5b : Verdict Routing ═══════════════════════════════
  ## Edge evaluation order matters: first match wins.

  ## Full migration achieved -> done
  review_verdict -> done when overall_parity

  ## Current batch done, plan next batch (with full verdict history for cross-batch learning)
  review_verdict -> plan_fanout when batch_complete as outer_loop(50) with {
    feature_manifest: "{{artifacts.feature_manifest}}",
    previous_progress: "{{outputs.review_verdict}}",
    previous_feedback: "{{outputs.review_verdict}}",
    batch_history: "{{outputs.review_verdict.history}}"
  }

  ## Current batch has bugs -> fix loop (max 5 hard cap)
  review_verdict -> fix when not batch_complete as fix_loop(5) with {
    _session_id: "{{outputs.claude_review._session_id}}",
    fix_plan: "{{outputs.claude_review.fix_plan}}",
    feature_manifest: "{{artifacts.feature_manifest}}",
    iterion_repo_path: "{{vars.iterion_repo_path}}",
    claw_repo_path: "{{vars.claw_repo_path}}"
  }

  ## Fallback: fix_loop exhausted but batch not complete -> re-plan anyway
  review_verdict -> plan_fanout when not overall_parity as outer_loop(50) with {
    feature_manifest: "{{artifacts.feature_manifest}}",
    previous_progress: "{{outputs.review_verdict}}",
    previous_feedback: "{{outputs.review_verdict}}",
    batch_history: "{{outputs.review_verdict.history}}"
  }

  ## Terminal fallback: all loops exhausted -> done (budget/iteration limit reached)
  review_verdict -> done

  ## ═══ Phase 6 : Fix with session continuity ════════════════════

  fix -> commit_namer with {
    _session_id: "{{outputs.fix._session_id}}"
  }
